    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:7ded129a-31ec-48db-84bf-95576ec2cbf5",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 56-year-old male who works as a warehouse supervisor, spending long hours on his feet directing stock movements and occasionally lifting heavy loads. He is of stocky build, standing 178 cm tall and weighing 97 kg, visibly overweight with a BMI placing him in the obese category. When he walks into the consultation room, he does so with a notable antalgic gait, favouring his right leg, his face subtly tightened with each step. He lowers himself into the chair slowly, straightening his right knee with visible discomfort before settling.\n\n{patientName} reports a dull, aching pain in both knees — more pronounced on the right — that has been worsening steadily over the past three years. The pain is worst in the morning, accompanied by stiffness lasting roughly 20–30 minutes before he can move freely. He also notes a grinding or creaking sensation in his knees when climbing stairs or rising from a seated position. By the end of a long shift at work, the pain becomes severe enough that he relies on over-the-counter ibuprofen almost daily.\n\nOutside of work, {patientName} used to enjoy recreational football with friends on weekends and gardening at home. Over the past year, he has almost entirely given up both activities due to pain. He now spends most evenings in his recliner watching sports on television, which he acknowledges has contributed to further weight gain. He lives with his wife of 28 years and has two adult children. He is socially active, enjoying barbecues and local community events, but feels increasingly limited and frustrated by his reduced mobility.\n\n{patientName} is a non-smoker but admits to drinking 3–4 beers on weekends. He has a moderate diet but consumes a high proportion of processed foods due to the physical demands and long hours of his job. He has never engaged in a structured exercise program and acknowledges that his weight has been increasing gradually since his late 30s. He is motivated to improve his condition but is apprehensive about the prospect of surgery."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
